Let $a = x + yi$ and $b = u + vi,$ where $x,$ $y,$ $u,$ and $v$ are real numbers.  Since $0,$ $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ are the vertices of a square in counterclockwise order, $b - a$ is a scalar multiple of $i(a - 0) = ai.$  In other words,
\[u + vi - (x + yi) = k(x + yi) i\]for some real number $k.$  This simplifies to
\[(u - x) + (v - y) i = (-ky) + (kx) i.\]Then $u - x = -ky$ and $v - y = kx.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

O = (0,0);
A = (1,0);
B = (1,1);
C = (0,1);

draw(O--A--B--C--cycle);

label("$0$", O, SW);
label("$a$", A, SE);
label("$b$", B, NE);
label("$c$", C, NW);
[/asy]

Since $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ are the vertices of a square, the length of $a$ is equal to the length of $b.$  Hence,
\[x^2 + y^2 = u^2 + v^2.\]From $u - x = -ky$ and $v - y = kx,$
\begin{align*}
u^2 &= (x - ky)^2 = x^2 - 2kxy + k^2 y^2, \\
v^2 &= (y + kx)^2 = y^2 + 2kxy + k^2 x^2.
\end{align*}Then $u^2 + v^2 = (1 + k^2) (x^2 + y^2),$ so $1 + k^2 = 1.$  Hence, $k = 0,$ which means $u = x$ and $v = y.$

Then $c = b + (b - a) = 2b - a = 2u + 2vi - (x + yi) = (2u - x) + (2v - y) i.$  Hence,
\begin{align*}
\frac{ac + b^2}{ab} &= \frac{(x + yi)((2u - x) + (2v - y) i) + (u + vi)^2}{(x + yi)(u + vi)} \\
&= \frac{(2ux - x^2 - 2vy) + (2uy + 2vx - xy) i + (u^2 - v^2) + 2uvi}{(xu - yv) + (xv + yu) i} \\
&= \frac{(2xu - x^2 - 2vy + u^2 - v^2) + (2uy + 2vx - xy + 2uv) i}{(xu - yv) + (xv + yu) i} \\
&= \frac{(x^2 - 2xu + u^2) + (2vy + v^2) + (2uy + 2vx - xy + 2uv) i}{(xu - yv) + (xv + yu) i} \\
&= \frac{(x - u)^2 + (v + y)^2 + (2uy + 2vx - xy + 2uv) i}{(xu - yv) + (xv + yu) i} \\
&= \frac{(x - u)^2 + (v + y)^2 + (2uy + 2vx - xy + 2uv) i}{(xu - yv) + (xv + yu) i} \cdot \frac{(xu - yv) - (xv + yu) i}{(xu - yv) - (xv + yu) i} \\
&= \frac{(x - u)^2 (xu - yv) + (v + y)^2 (xu - yv) + (2uy + 2vx - xy + 2uv)(xv + yu) + [(x - u)^2 + (v + y)^2](xv + yu)}{(xu - yv)^2 + (xv + yu)^2}.
\end{align*}Since $u = x$ and $v = y,$ this simplifies to $\boxed{1}.$
